ce:section.ce:para:
Raman spectroscopy was used in this study to determine the quality of the GQDs and their nanoconjugates. The two characteristic bands of GQDs in Raman spectrum are known as the G-band (sp2) tangential mode and the D-disorder band (breathing mode, sp3). The G-band observed at 1554 cm−1 for GQDs alone, is a result of in-plane vibrations of sp2 bonded carbon atoms, whereas the D-band at 1385 cm-1 is due to out-of-plane vibrations attributed to the presence of structural defects (Fig. 5
                           ) [48,49]. Upon conjugation of the phthalocyanines to the GQDs, the G bands of the GQDs shifted to higher and the D bands to lower frequencies as shown (Fig. 5). The G-bands in the conjugates were observed at 1595, 1591 and 1595 cm−1 for 2@GQDs, 3@GQDs and 4@GQDs respectively, while the D bands were observed around 1290 cm−1 for all the conjugates. Shifts in the Raman frequencies are often indicative of strong π electron interactions in hybrid materials [50]. The quality of the GQDs was determined by measuring the ratio of the intensities of the D and G bands (ID
                           /IG
                           ). The ID
                           /IG
                            was 1.26 for GQDs, 1.51 for 2@GQDs, 1.35 for 3@GQDs and 1.31 for 4@GQDs. The D band increases in intensity following the π-π interaction between GQDs with the Pcs confirms the increase in the structural disorder of the GQDs.
